UML:TaggedValue.value: Package of concrete feature types used in the context of observations. General observations may be made on _any_ feature type (?) but some features-of-interest would not be instantiated if the observation activity was not taking place. Thus these feature types that are only used for observations are intrinsically part of the observations package ...

The eventTime is modelled as a generalized TimeObject. It will often be a geometric primitive, such as an instant or period, but (e.g.) recurrent events may be associated with a temporal geometric complex.
"source" describes the pre-conditions or input-state; "product" the post-conditions or result-state.

Some classes substitutable for AbstractFeature (e.g. xmml:Site, xmml:Specimen) know about "relatedObservations" on the source end of the association. However, in general the association is unidirectional.
Concrete classes derived from AbstractObservation must add at least one "result" property of the appropriate type. The data-type of the result controls the ObservationType.

UML:Constraint.name: Concrete specialization MUST carry a result

UML:TaggedValue.value: Concrete classes derived from AbstractObservation must add at least one "result" property of the appropriate type. The data-type of the result controls the ObservationType.

This association provides the semantic-type of the observation. From this conceptual POV observations are soft-typed, since their structure is not determined by the type. This is necessary since the set of possible PropertyDefinitions is essentially infinite, especially given the fact that a PropertyDefinition may be compound. The property is optional, since it may be omitted on specialised observation types.

The procedure that is the target of this association will often not be observation-instance specific, but rather a description of a generic procedure, instrument, etc. However, if it is necessary to record instance-specific details, parameters, inputs, etc, then a specific procedure-instance should be used.
This type may be used as the type of the Observation/result where the value is provided as an independent resource identified by a URI.
A location property is inherited from Event. This should be the location of the *Observation Event* - i.e. the location of the sensor or instrument at the moment of observation.

Observations are soft-typed concerning their semantics. This is necessary since the set of possible PhenomenonDefinitions is essentially infinite, especially given the fact that a PhenomenonDefinition may be compound.

time The eventTime is modelled as a generalized TimeObject. It will often be a geometric primitive, such as an instant or period, but (e.g.) recurrent events may be associated with a temporal geometric complex.
When the Procedure is a Sensor, this dependency is a directed association with the rolename "observable".

The Observation feature supports an event-centric or user-centric view. The "observation" description is a map of all of the properties associated with a particular information capture event, including its result.
This contrasts with the Sensor feature, which provides a process-centric viewpoint. The "sensor system" description is effectively a map of of the properties of all potential information capture events _except_ the results.

The procedure that is the target of this association will often be a description of a generic procedure, instrument, etc. However, if it is necessary to record instance-specific details, parameters, inputs, etc, then a specific procedure-instance should be used. For example, a CategoryObservation event will use a classification-procedure that may depend on more primitive observations - e.g. a set of prior measurements. As part of the description of the procedure it may be useful to be able to record these sources or inputs. It is preferable to partition these considerations with the "Procedure" rather than promoting special properties ("inputs", "source") up to the Observation class. This is consistent with some mission-specific parameters being associated with the sensor, as is done in SensorML. However, the most appropriate partioning of the generic (static) and instance specific (dynamic) information between the Observation feature and the Procedure/Sensor is to some extent arbitrary.

Generic concrete observation type, in which the result is "anyType". Note that this class is a *sibling*, rather than parent, to the specialized convenience observation types.
Note that he result may be a pointer to a value (stream) available out-of-band (e.g. from another service). This supports the case where the client is primarily interested in listening to a result-stream, or where the result is expressed in some other conventional format (e.g. imagery). In this contect the Observation instance provides the "metadata" for the result, primarily concerning the data-capture event.
In an XML instance an xsi:type attribute may provide the schema-level information indicating the structure of the result.
Target Location may be provided by * the Sensor Model (remote sensors) * the sensor location (in situ sensors) * the sampling location (specimens)
The Procedure must be commensurate with the Phenomenon being observed. The phenomenon-definition is treated as a first-class property of observation in order to support discovery and data fusion.
This type may be used as the type of the Observation/result where the value is provided as an independent resource identified by a URI.

Generic concrete observation type, in which the result type is "Any". The datatype of the result is indicated at runtime, for example using the xsi:type attribute. The result may also be a pointer to a value (stream) available out-of-band (e.g. from another service). This supports the case where the client is primarily interested in listening to a result-stream, or where the result is expressed in some other conventional format (e.g. imagery). In this context the Observation instance provides the "metadata" for the result, primarily concerning the data-capture event.
Note that this class is a *sibling*, rather than parent, to the specialized convenience observation types.
Concrete observation type in which the result is an interleaved stream. The structure and encoding of the stream are provided in the adjacent properties.
Concrete observation type in which the result is an interleaved stream, encoded using the Data components from SensorML.

Convenience observation type where the result is a text value from some controlled vocabulary or authority or follows some lexical pattern. The source of the vocabulary, authority, or pattern for the result (its "codeSpace") is defined separately, and indicated via a URI link from the result to the codeSpace definition.
Generic class for description of procedures. In the context of observations these may be specialized as Sensors and Instruments, Calculations and Simulators.
"source" describes the pre-conditions or input-state; "product" the post-conditions or result-state.

Package of concrete feature types used in the context of observations. General observations may be made on _any_ feature type (?) but some features-of-interest would not be instantiated if the observation activity was not taking place. Thus these feature types that are only used for observations are intrinsically part of the observations package ...

Provisional
Specialised coverage used to record the set of offset,direction values conventionally used when surveying a traverse, borehole, etc
Required if position CRS is 2D; DirectPosition in this case will be a 1D coordinate in a 1D CRS (i.e. a datum and scale)

Site is the top of a hierarchy of classes describing features whose primary role is to provide locations for sampling and in-situ observations, such as Station, Traverse, Section, Borehole, Flightline. Instances of these feature-types are not defined by the variation of any intrinsic property, such as a geological concept, but are artefacts of the observation process, either conceptual or constructed.

A Specimen is some physical material sampled from a specified location, typically associated with a Site, such as a Station, a location or interval within a Section, or a location or extent from a DescriptionExtent
For more detailed constraints, must use sensor response model
